1
00:00:02,274 --> 00:00:14,694
The Factors of Enlightenment While the hindrances describe the difficulties we meet in meditation, the factors of enlightenment are the abilities we develop in meditation.

2
00:00:16,096 --> 00:00:21,504
Bhante uses the image of wild geese in flight and I found this very helpful.

3
00:00:22,585 --> 00:00:24,149
The leader is mindfulness.

4
00:00:25,149 --> 00:00:27,574
In support there are two flanks.

5
00:00:28,347 --> 00:00:41,054
If you watch wild geese, you will often find one flank flying more in the slipstream of the leader, taking it easy, while the other flank is spread out, almost as if they are vying to take over the lead.

6
00:00:42,939 --> 00:00:47,048
That's a very helpful image for these supporting factors.

7
00:00:47,246 --> 00:00:51,051
Three of them are calming, helping us to take it easy.

8
00:00:51,091 --> 00:00:58,841
These three are concentration, equanimity and tranquility.

9
00:01:00,564 --> 00:01:04,287
Then there is the wide flank, encouraging us to push ahead.

10
00:01:05,328 --> 00:01:10,656
These are energy, investigation of Dhamma and joy.

11
00:01:12,525 --> 00:01:17,292
So let's look in more detail at the seven factors which develop as we meditate.

12
00:01:19,795 --> 00:01:21,117
Starting with mindfulness.

13
00:01:22,597 --> 00:01:28,144
It's ironic that this factor which is essentially so simple is also so hard to describe.

14
00:01:29,908 --> 00:01:31,870
It's a bit easier to describe what it's not.

15
00:01:33,191 --> 00:01:40,760
Mindfulness is not thinking or dreaming or planning or remembering or trying to work out what life is all about.

16
00:01:42,495 --> 00:01:56,635
It's the potential we have to know that we're thinking or dreaming or planning and so on, as well as to feel the moods and emotions underlying all the mental activity and the physical sensations that accompany all this.

17
00:01:59,018 --> 00:02:01,882
So much of our lives we are caught up in mental activity.

18
00:02:01,921 --> 00:02:05,566
This is the doing aspect of our minds.

19
00:02:06,155 --> 00:02:16,638
We're fascinated by our own thoughts and opinions, our stories about what happened in the past and what's going to happen in the future, our speculations on what life is all about.

20
00:02:18,382 --> 00:02:26,239
We lose touch with the potential for the human mind to simply know experience without trying to do anything at all.

21
00:02:29,509 --> 00:02:45,204
To practice mindfulness we tune into the raw data that is coming into our mind sounds, physical sensations and the feelings produced by moods and emotions as well as the thoughts that emerge from the mind as it tries to process all this.

22
00:02:47,205 --> 00:02:51,549
We encourage ourselves to drop the fascination with the detail of our thoughts.

23
00:02:52,990 --> 00:02:58,335
It doesn't mean we have to stop thinking but to know that a thought is happening whenever it is.

24
00:03:01,082 --> 00:03:06,991
So this basic potential of our minds to know experience is the leading factor of enlightenment.

25
00:03:08,992 --> 00:03:13,838
It's hard for us to believe that just knowing is so powerful spiritually.

26
00:03:15,020 --> 00:03:19,787
We feel we have to do something about whatever we know in order to get anywhere.

27
00:03:21,288 --> 00:03:26,735
But gradually we come to accept that it is our misunderstandings that lead us into trouble.

28
00:03:28,775 --> 00:03:32,820
We are reacting too quickly without fully knowing what is going on.

29
00:03:34,604 --> 00:03:46,141
As we acknowledge this, we become more willing to spend time gathering the raw data, getting to know the feelings and emotions that drive our thinking mind.

30
00:03:50,341 --> 00:03:54,449
So mindfulness is our first tool in learning what life is all about.

31
00:03:55,350 --> 00:03:57,574
Simple data gathering you could say.

32
00:03:57,616 --> 00:04:00,441
Getting the feel for the situation.

33
00:04:02,125 --> 00:04:04,889
Letting ourselves dwell in the here and now.

34
00:04:07,485 --> 00:04:09,508
Let's look at the supporting factors now.

35
00:04:09,548 --> 00:04:13,432
First in the slipstream is concentration.

36
00:04:14,274 --> 00:04:19,660
But that word can crinkle our foreheads because we associate it with doing hard sums at school.

37
00:04:19,680 --> 00:04:23,004
The word focus is sometimes used.

38
00:04:24,245 --> 00:04:26,007
We direct our attention at something.

39
00:04:26,827 --> 00:04:31,333
Usually in meditation we start off by focusing on the sensations of breathing.

40
00:04:33,153 --> 00:04:38,901
The Pali word for this factor is Samadhi, which gives the sense of the mind resting.

41
00:04:40,283 --> 00:04:46,230
So this factor rests the mind in the sensations of breathing or some other focus for attention.

42
00:04:48,814 --> 00:04:50,598
Why does it help to focus attention?

43
00:04:52,079 --> 00:04:57,547
One reason is that it helps us stay present rather than get distracted into daydreams and fantasies.

44
00:04:59,329 --> 00:05:03,074
It also quiets the mind when its range of interest is limited.

45
00:05:04,321 --> 00:05:08,848
and when we have a narrow focus for attention we can go deeper into that phenomenon.

46
00:05:10,471 --> 00:05:11,913
Think of using a telescope.

47
00:05:13,336 --> 00:05:21,971
You have to look through a narrow tube so your range of vision is limited, but you can see far more clearly within this narrow range.

48
00:05:24,555 --> 00:05:30,345
Happily the Dhamma can be learned from anything, no matter how small or seemingly insignificant.

49
00:05:31,338 --> 00:05:40,351
The four noble truths, the wheel of dependent origination, these are sewn into each sensation of the tummy rising and falling.

50
00:05:42,509 --> 00:05:45,713
In essence then, any focus for attention will do.

51
00:05:47,113 --> 00:05:54,983
We normally start with the breath because this anchors our mind in physical reality, so our meditation is grounded, embodied.

52
00:05:56,125 --> 00:05:59,509
Also, those sensations are often felt as calming.

53
00:06:00,329 --> 00:06:08,819
If not, then try various touch points, the hands resting in the lap, the feet on the ground, etc.,

54
00:06:10,218 --> 00:06:13,762
whatever sensations provide the easiest resting place for the mind.

55
00:06:17,608 --> 00:06:25,762
Once our usual fascination with stories and thoughts has shifted towards fascination for present experience, we can loosen this focus.

56
00:06:27,004 --> 00:06:31,170
Loosening the focus lets our minds be more natural, more ordinary.

57
00:06:31,189 --> 00:06:35,516
And that's what we want to get to know, our ordinary mind.

58
00:06:36,745 --> 00:06:44,096
So if a sound or an itchy feeling attracts attention, we can let the mind focus on these and learn the Dhamma there.

59
00:06:45,858 --> 00:06:48,723
We let the mind dwell wherever it is naturally drawn.

60
00:06:51,487 --> 00:06:54,951
I don't know about you, but my mind is naturally drawn to detail.

61
00:06:56,074 --> 00:07:02,504
When I rest attention in any feeling, a sort of fascination sets up, a longing to know it more deeply.

62
00:07:03,444 --> 00:07:05,367
So I like the narrow focus.

63
00:07:06,579 --> 00:07:17,797
But when that fascination leads to a sense of straining to see more deeply, then I need to widen my focus to see the broader picture and include that very sense of straining.

64
00:07:17,836 --> 00:07:21,362
Otherwise, I start getting uptight.

65
00:07:22,884 --> 00:07:27,170
When I feel the strain mindfully, I often find that I can relax again.

66
00:07:29,377 --> 00:07:40,492
And whenever a strong emotion comes up, it's usually best to broaden the focus, to take in the full mind-body system and feel how this emotion is embodied.

67
00:07:41,853 --> 00:07:48,581
We feel the sensations, the threads of aversion and desire, the thought stream that might be erupting.

68
00:07:51,125 --> 00:07:59,115
When the emotion has burned away a bit, we might again be drawn to some focus in the body, often the kernel of the emotion's energy.

69
00:08:00,158 --> 00:08:06,987
Attending to this, we might hear the thoughts and sense the feelings that bind us to the emotional state.

70
00:08:08,990 --> 00:08:17,322
This ability to focus and to broaden and narrow the focus as necessary is a great aid in deepening our self-knowledge.

71
00:08:20,358 --> 00:08:27,569
Let's look at one of the factors in the wide flank now which pairs up with concentration so that the two balance one another out.

72
00:08:28,829 --> 00:08:30,572
This is the factor of energy.

73
00:08:32,034 --> 00:08:34,057
We need energy to accomplish anything.

74
00:08:35,200 --> 00:08:39,245
In meditation we need enough physical energy to sit upright or walk.

75
00:08:40,147 --> 00:08:45,774
Sounds easy but remember those attacks of sleepiness how desperately we long to lie down.

76
00:08:47,408 --> 00:08:50,534
We also need the mental energy of resolution.

77
00:08:51,356 --> 00:08:52,899
We resolve to be mindful.

78
00:08:54,845 --> 00:09:01,840
Every time we notice the mind has been wandering and come back to the breath, we are strengthening this factor of enlightenment.

79
00:09:04,267 --> 00:09:09,294
When this factor is working well, we are alert and enthusiastic about the practice.

80
00:09:10,277 --> 00:09:17,268
We are fascinated by present experience and have a sense of zeal, a buzzing dedication to the here and now.

81
00:09:17,307 --> 00:09:22,976
At other times our energies go low and we can easily sink into the hindrances.

82
00:09:24,239 --> 00:09:29,548
Then again, we can get overly energised, striving impatiently for insight.

83
00:09:31,672 --> 00:09:36,023
We strengthen the factor whenever we work skilfully with the hindrance of sleepiness.

84
00:09:37,447 --> 00:09:41,857
At these times we often need to find a more stimulating focus than the breath.

85
00:09:43,160 --> 00:09:46,489
That's the idea behind opening the eyes, standing up etc.

86
00:09:46,528 --> 00:09:47,993
that we discussed yesterday.

87
00:09:49,254 --> 00:09:56,485
Physical exercise is naturally energising, so going quite fast for the first few minutes of the walking meditation session helps.

88
00:09:57,186 --> 00:10:04,918
We can also stimulate ourselves mentally by reflecting on whatever inspired us to take up meditation practice and to come on retreat.

89
00:10:07,301 --> 00:10:13,009
At times we can get over-energised, uptight and breathless with enthusiasm and zeal.

90
00:10:13,068 --> 00:10:19,177
Again, it can help to broaden the focus to give more room for the energy to burn off.

91
00:10:20,542 --> 00:10:23,904
Feeling the whole body can help, as can opening the eyes.

92
00:10:25,446 --> 00:10:33,413
Walking around the paddocks, rather than the short span used for walking meditation, can also burn off some pent-up craving for progress.

93
00:10:35,254 --> 00:10:42,041
We can also talk ourselves down, reminding ourselves to take it easy, that everything is fine, just as it is.

94
00:10:44,342 --> 00:10:49,366
These two factors, concentration and energy, help each other out.

95
00:10:50,663 --> 00:10:55,849
When our energies are too high or too low, it usually helps to have a broad focus.

96
00:10:57,009 --> 00:11:04,739
When they are more balanced, the narrow focus channels all the energy into the Dhamma of each passing sensation and feeling.

97
00:11:07,881 --> 00:11:10,043
Looking now at the next two supports.

98
00:11:11,265 --> 00:11:16,991
In the slipstream we have equanimity and on the wide flank is investigation.

99
00:11:19,418 --> 00:11:23,302
Equanimity is that balance of mind that counters reactivity.

100
00:11:24,482 --> 00:11:30,048
It is the willingness not to seize every passing pleasure or oppose every passing irritant.

101
00:11:30,950 --> 00:11:32,270
It lets things be.

102
00:11:35,073 --> 00:11:45,865
We strengthen equanimity every time we work skilfully with desire and aversion, gradually learning to let go of our addictions and surrender to what we dislike.

103
00:11:47,278 --> 00:11:49,400
This doesn't mean we become a marshmallow.

104
00:11:51,322 --> 00:11:54,106
We can still strive for what we feel is right and good.

105
00:11:55,849 --> 00:11:59,852
But the striving is not stressing us out or blinding us to others' needs.

106
00:12:01,014 --> 00:12:04,118
It's a balanced movement towards an attainable goal.

107
00:12:06,120 --> 00:12:09,844
Likewise, we can oppose wrongdoing with equanimity.

108
00:12:10,937 --> 00:12:20,732
Great peacemakers like Nelson Mandela and Gandhi exemplify this, responding to injustice and oppression with wisdom rather than hatred.

109
00:12:24,018 --> 00:12:29,065
Equanimity develops naturally as we see how phenomena arise and pass away.

110
00:12:30,866 --> 00:12:47,796
We can reflect on this on the broad scale, seeing how ephemeral are fashions and celebrities, for example, how people and institutions and political parties come to power and later fall from grace, how civilizations have died out.

111
00:12:48,990 --> 00:12:50,472
We can see it in our own lives.

112
00:12:51,414 --> 00:12:57,884
Many of the hopes and ambitions that fuelled us when we were young may be largely forgotten in middle and older age.

113
00:12:59,086 --> 00:13:02,791
Many cherished possessions and close relationships will have been lost.

114
00:13:05,754 --> 00:13:09,400
Mindfulness helps us to see this in the minutiae of life.

115
00:13:10,562 --> 00:13:15,048
How each thought, emotion, sensation appears and disappears.

116
00:13:16,496 --> 00:13:45,120
we start asking ourselves what's the point in getting all hot and bothered about this it will fade away in a few moments now that might sound as though we're distancing ourselves from life but mindfulness doesn't work at a distance it's a touchy-feely kind of learning up close and personal so the wisdom behind equanimity is very sensitive to our needs and desires and aversions

117
00:13:46,754 --> 00:13:56,288
The willingness not to react comes from seeing again and again how futile it is to try to hold on to pleasure or avoid pain.

118
00:13:58,792 --> 00:14:06,042
As we experience the suffering caused by these reactions, we are persuaded to give up forcing things to be the way we want them to be.

119
00:14:09,748 --> 00:14:15,275
Paradoxically, once we stop forcing, we find something else disappears as well.

120
00:14:16,909 --> 00:14:20,212
The problem we were trying to overcome vanishes without trace.

121
00:14:21,615 --> 00:14:24,076
I couldn't see this clearly for many, many years.

122
00:14:25,438 --> 00:14:29,322
It even frightened me, the sudden loss of focus for my energies.

123
00:14:31,205 --> 00:14:44,317
While I struggled with moods and emotions, trying to get on top of things, there was at least a clear sense of what I was doing, struggling to solve a problem that, in my mind anyhow, desperately needed solving.

124
00:14:45,445 --> 00:14:52,375
Then there came the moment of surrender and the loss of any boundary against which I could push.

125
00:14:53,998 --> 00:14:56,701
It was so confusing I couldn't see the beauty in it.

126
00:14:59,807 --> 00:15:04,594
Nowadays I'm much more used to the space that can open up when we stop reacting.

127
00:15:05,595 --> 00:15:07,317
It doesn't frighten me so much.

128
00:15:08,446 --> 00:15:18,258
I'm more willing to acknowledge the space and the fact that it has never actually hurt or threatened me in any way, despite all my mistrust and suspicions.

129
00:15:20,360 --> 00:15:24,184
As I grow easier with the space, my mind broadens.

130
00:15:25,466 --> 00:15:28,951
I find I can see things more easily from the other person's point of view.

131
00:15:30,133 --> 00:15:33,677
I'm more open to discussion, less frightened of failure.

132
00:15:35,480 --> 00:15:47,356
So this is the factor of equanimity, a spaciousness that allows what we like and dislike to come and go without the need to clutch what we like and destroy what we dislike.

133
00:15:48,979 --> 00:15:52,183
It's a soothing quality which steadies mindfulness.

134
00:15:56,109 --> 00:16:02,077
Equanimity is in the slipstream and is balanced on the wide flank by investigation.

135
00:16:03,289 --> 00:16:09,099
By this we mean investigation of Dhamma, discovering the teaching for ourselves.

136
00:16:11,822 --> 00:16:19,114
By comparison to equanimity, which has been very challenging for me, this factor of investigation comes more naturally.

137
00:16:20,395 --> 00:16:23,421
It may have helped that I was always intrigued by the mystery of life.

138
00:16:24,221 --> 00:16:25,244
Where did I come from?

139
00:16:26,144 --> 00:16:26,966
Why am I here?

140
00:16:27,868 --> 00:16:29,230
What's life all about?

141
00:16:30,677 --> 00:16:38,210
I enjoy learning, and the notion that I can learn the Dhamma for myself, from my own experience, still thrills me.

142
00:16:41,254 --> 00:16:46,043
One teaching we can investigate during meditation is the teaching around anicca .

143
00:16:49,368 --> 00:16:55,538
We can take an interest in the start and end of each breath, each footstep, each sensation

144
00:16:57,408 --> 00:17:04,698
This draws us from our usual preoccupation with facts and concepts, which give the world a sense of solidity and predictability.

145
00:17:06,661 --> 00:17:13,451
The study of anicca engages us with the more fluid sense of reality as it appears at our sense door.

146
00:17:13,951 --> 00:17:18,538
We can also study the other characteristics of existence, anatta and dukkha.

147
00:17:19,902 --> 00:17:28,534
I'm especially drawn to the whole question of dukkha, to see can I pinpoint any source of stress, suffering or dissatisfaction in my experience.

148
00:17:29,875 --> 00:17:31,959
To take one example of working with aversion.

149
00:17:33,240 --> 00:17:42,032
At one level, I might kind of know I'm fed up with all this meditation business, for example, wishing it was over and I could do something active and worthwhile.

150
00:17:42,933 --> 00:17:47,901
There may also be a strong resistance to acknowledging this, never mind investigating it deeper.

151
00:17:49,383 --> 00:17:52,868
That first step is often the hardest, acknowledging.

152
00:17:54,332 --> 00:18:04,169
If I can get over that and simply note, OK, this is bad humour, disinterest, not wanting to meditate, then the factor of investigation starts to kick in.

153
00:18:05,351 --> 00:18:07,474
How is this bad humour felt in my body?

154
00:18:07,515 --> 00:18:11,121
Is it my jaw, my stomach?

155
00:18:12,721 --> 00:18:19,212
My attention would be drawn towards the unpleasant sensations and I begin to get warily curious about them.

156
00:18:19,913 --> 00:18:20,655
Are they stinging?

157
00:18:21,698 --> 00:18:22,459
Are they aching?

158
00:18:23,461 --> 00:18:24,823
Is it tightness I'm feeling?

159
00:18:26,486 --> 00:18:34,340
I might also begin to catch fleeting glimpses of pleasant sensations and sense the tight grip with which I'm holding onto these.

160
00:18:35,519 --> 00:18:45,432
I might realise that the pleasantness gives a sense of self, insisting, this is mine, I need this, or some variation on this theme.

161
00:18:47,255 --> 00:18:55,806
The unpleasant sensations and associated bad humour loosen a bit to show an underlying fear that my sense of self is being threatened.

162
00:18:58,128 --> 00:19:01,594
By then I'm generally hooked on this present moment detective story.

163
00:19:02,991 --> 00:19:14,482
And if I can maintain mindfulness with all its supporting factors, the crisis always resolves to give me a deeper understanding of how this being, I call me, is composed.

164
00:19:15,944 --> 00:19:23,913
With this understanding comes compassion for the stresses and strains around the kernel of goodness at the core of each human being.

165
00:19:27,215 --> 00:19:32,121
This kind of investigation teaches me the truth of anatta, not self.

166
00:19:33,535 --> 00:19:44,685
I feel how quickly and automatically I identify with pleasant mind states like clarity, meta, happiness, and how hard it is to admit to unpleasant states like bad humour.

167
00:19:45,967 --> 00:19:52,993
Because of delusion, I believe I should be in control of my mind, always able to get myself into some shade of good humour.

168
00:19:53,994 --> 00:20:02,022
Again and again I learn that this mind-body complex has a life of its own and that my level of control is very limited.

169
00:20:03,251 --> 00:20:08,998
This is a demonstration of anatta, that there's no one in charge of this entity I call me.

170
00:20:10,759 --> 00:20:24,972
It's a very hard truth to digest, but the more often I feel my whole being relax as I let go of trying to control matters, the more persuaded I am that the sense of anatta is a very beautiful one.

171
00:20:28,215 --> 00:20:32,500
The investigation also teaches us about dukkha and the cause of dukkha.

172
00:20:33,424 --> 00:20:42,220
Again and again we verify the second noble truth, that dukkha results from us wanting to be different to how they are right now.

173
00:20:44,696 --> 00:20:49,260
Equanimity and investigation make good partners, balancing one another out.

174
00:20:50,521 --> 00:20:55,406
When we are equanimous, the mind feels good, steady, balanced, peaceful.

175
00:20:56,186 --> 00:21:03,314
Without investigation, that could become a lovely resting place for the mind, a lovely experience but not leading anywhere.

176
00:21:03,354 --> 00:21:14,703
But if the factor of investigation is aroused, we get curious about that lovely, balanced steadiness, and often a subtle clinging will be revealed.

177
00:21:14,683 --> 00:21:17,946
Perhaps there is self-congratulating going on.

178
00:21:18,988 --> 00:21:21,150
Amn't I wonderful to have such equanimity?

179
00:21:21,711 --> 00:21:23,132
At last I'm getting somewhere.

180
00:21:23,172 --> 00:21:35,683
As those little background whispers of thought are revealed, we may also feel a sense of holding, as if there is a hand in our mind clutching the steadiness and holding on to it.

181
00:21:36,984 --> 00:21:42,210
That sense of holding contains tinges of anxiety, fear and loss.

182
00:21:42,798 --> 00:21:48,951
And so the mind may not feel so steady anymore as we feel ourselves grasping the state of equanimity.

183
00:21:50,153 --> 00:21:53,642
So this turns into an encounter with the hindrance of desire.

184
00:21:54,663 --> 00:21:57,549
In this case, desire for an equanimous mind.

185
00:21:58,626 --> 00:22:06,414
Although our peaceful meditation is lost, we are on the path, learning how to enjoy equanimity without the pain of clinging to it.

186
00:22:07,055 --> 00:22:15,083
On the other hand, when investigation is very strong, we can be buzzing with excitement, determined to get to the bottom of whatever is intriguing us.

187
00:22:15,983 --> 00:22:24,211
Perhaps it's a mind state like judgment, for example, and we get really curious about how this is felt in the body and mind.

188
00:22:24,192 --> 00:22:30,159
If we're not careful, our curiosity can get the better of us and we're unwittingly putting ourselves under pressure.

189
00:22:31,980 --> 00:22:37,887
We can get entangled with the judging mind and start judging ourselves because we can't see things clearly.

190
00:22:37,928 --> 00:22:43,934
Once we notice this, we need to try to get back to a more balanced state of mind.

191
00:22:44,875 --> 00:22:46,718
So equanimity is our strength here.

192
00:22:47,198 --> 00:22:51,042
The ability to persuade ourselves that the lack of clarity is not a big deal.

193
00:22:51,763 --> 00:22:53,085
Nothing to get worked up about.

194
00:22:55,073 --> 00:22:58,798
So let's look at the final pair now, tranquility and joy.

195
00:22:58,858 --> 00:23:04,426
Tranquility, as you can guess, is in the slipstream, calming us down.

196
00:23:05,367 --> 00:23:07,832
Joy on the wide flank, urging us on.

197
00:23:09,615 --> 00:23:12,239
Tranquility is very much bound up with equanimity.

198
00:23:12,980 --> 00:23:17,826
When the mind is balanced and equanimous, the heart feels tranquil, at ease.

199
00:23:18,769 --> 00:23:23,055
And tranquility is strengthened when we work skilfully with restlessness.

200
00:23:24,740 --> 00:23:26,663
Tranquility was a late developer for me.

201
00:23:26,702 --> 00:23:33,211
As I look back on it, I can see that I was ignoring whatever little suggestions of calm were on offer.

202
00:23:33,972 --> 00:23:38,098
They didn't attract my attention, which was zooming in on stronger emotions.

203
00:23:39,381 --> 00:23:45,128
I was so intent on solving all my emotional problems that I skipped over those moments of ease.

204
00:23:45,170 --> 00:23:49,296
I'm still plagued by fears and self-doubt.

205
00:23:49,536 --> 00:23:50,998
I'm nowhere near enlightenment.

206
00:23:51,638 --> 00:23:53,801
What does it matter that there's a moment's peace?

207
00:23:55,115 --> 00:23:57,079
Those moments seemed irrelevant.

208
00:23:57,923 --> 00:24:02,575
It took a long time for me to be able to admit, just now, I'm not stressed out.

209
00:24:03,036 --> 00:24:04,820
Just now, things are okay.

210
00:24:06,926 --> 00:24:14,458
But once I got myself around to noticing what relaxation actually felt like, I started developing a taste for that experience.

211
00:24:15,499 --> 00:24:24,553
My determination to solve all my emotional problems dwindled slightly, and to my surprise, some of them solved themselves without me at the helm.

212
00:24:26,134 --> 00:24:36,630
So I would advise you to get curious about ease, to take a real interest, even if it's only momentary, or just marginally easier than normal.

213
00:24:36,609 --> 00:24:46,101
The danger is that we judge, this isn't worth anything, I'm still totally uptight, and so the slightest relaxation is snuffed out immediately.

214
00:24:47,843 --> 00:24:54,089
This kind of thinking may be quite prevalent in the West because our culture puts so much emphasis on success.

215
00:24:55,471 --> 00:25:01,538
We want to be totally relaxed and floating in the clouds before we can judge ourselves to be any way tranquil.

216
00:25:02,125 --> 00:25:07,078
but we can only learn tranquility if we build on whatever small morsels we are offered.

217
00:25:08,804 --> 00:25:16,928
The wonderful thing is that tranquility feels lovely, and so once we tune into it at all, we are naturally interested in developing it.

218
00:25:18,393 --> 00:25:31,807
Nowadays I find it can really help me through the storms of emotion to be able to discern any little chink in my arm or attention and to feel the gorgeous sensations that are released when we relax a tight muscle for a moment.

219
00:25:32,989 --> 00:25:40,036
This helps me persuade to give up on useless battles and make peace with whatever I am sensing as a problem.

220
00:25:43,079 --> 00:25:46,222
Balancing tranquility on the wide flank we have joy.

221
00:25:47,434 --> 00:25:56,182
At times it may be hard to believe, but we can actually get hooked on the present moment and really appreciate and enjoy meditation.

222
00:25:57,743 --> 00:26:00,385
This factor is very much linked with investigation.

223
00:26:01,846 --> 00:26:08,152
As we investigate, we get interested in our experience, and interest is in itself a form of joy.

224
00:26:08,192 --> 00:26:12,155
If you're interested in a book or a film, you are enjoying it.

225
00:26:13,237 --> 00:26:17,339
Think how much you enjoy any hobby, even if it's hard work at times.

226
00:26:19,513 --> 00:26:26,805
We can fall into the same trap as for tranquility and expect to feel elated and rapturous whenever this factor is working.

227
00:26:27,787 --> 00:26:31,192
But if you ask yourself at times, am I interested in this?

228
00:26:31,972 --> 00:26:34,477
I imagine the answer will often be yes.

229
00:26:35,518 --> 00:26:39,243
That might help you discern the quality of joy in your meditation.

230
00:26:41,114 --> 00:26:46,884
To strengthen this quality, it also helps to take more interest in pleasant sensations and moods.

231
00:26:47,926 --> 00:26:54,960
Sometimes we are so intent on seeing dukkha and its cause that we ignore sources of pleasure, thinking them irrelevant.

232
00:26:56,102 --> 00:27:01,131
But the Buddha teaches us about suffering and the end of suffering.

233
00:27:02,208 --> 00:27:04,992
So we also need to get curious about pleasure.

234
00:27:06,114 --> 00:27:11,884
We need to sensitize ourselves to those fleeting moments when we're not caught up in stress and suffering.

235
00:27:13,226 --> 00:27:16,131
These moments are precious and need nurturing.

236
00:27:17,413 --> 00:27:22,582
It's so easy for them to be slapped down by the judgmental mind saying, that's nothing.

237
00:27:22,842 --> 00:27:24,704
Think of all my real problems.

238
00:27:26,557 --> 00:27:31,404
Another way we can hinder joy is by being overly fearful of indulging it.

239
00:27:32,467 --> 00:27:39,778
We've heard the teaching around indulging pleasure and want to avoid that mistake, so we shy away from pleasant feelings.

240
00:27:41,140 --> 00:27:46,887
But if we're in the present moment rather than lost in thought, there's no danger of indulging.

241
00:27:47,990 --> 00:27:52,616
We'll feel the sense of clinging whenever it happens and that will do its own teaching.

242
00:27:54,352 --> 00:27:56,856
It's a mistake to be afraid of indulging joy.

243
00:27:57,417 --> 00:28:00,082
What we're actually doing is indulging fear.

244
00:28:01,806 --> 00:28:05,372
So when any suggestion of joy comes along, go for it.

245
00:28:06,354 --> 00:28:10,141
We need to let our minds get familiar with this lovely experience.

246
00:28:11,844 --> 00:28:16,932
Our minds welcome what they're familiar with and shy away from unfamiliar states.

247
00:28:17,555 --> 00:28:22,903
So the better we get to know joy, the more easily our mind will find it in the future.

248
00:28:22,942 --> 00:28:25,066
It's a win-win situation.

249
00:28:26,387 --> 00:28:30,012
You can trust mindfulness to sort out any clinging.

250
00:28:34,259 --> 00:28:38,305
At times you might feel some pleasant tingling sensations in your body.

251
00:28:38,345 --> 00:28:41,148
These are a manifestation of joy.

252
00:28:42,277 --> 00:28:46,903
Let your attention dwell there so as to strengthen this factor of enlightenment.

253
00:28:47,744 --> 00:28:53,554
And if at any stage you sense gladness in your meditation, really let it rip.

254
00:28:54,756 --> 00:29:01,846
Relax into the experience and give yourself full permission to enjoy for as long as it lasts.

255
00:29:04,250 --> 00:29:08,857
These last factors of tranquility and joy make natural partners.

256
00:29:10,019 --> 00:29:15,669
Joy energises tranquillity, prevents us slipping off to a nice tranquil sleep.

257
00:29:17,090 --> 00:29:21,939
And tranquillity calms joy, preventing it run off into excitement.

258
00:29:24,824 --> 00:29:27,347
Before I finish, a word of warning.

259
00:29:29,070 --> 00:29:34,760
We can easily start beating ourselves up for not feeling all these beautiful factors of mind.

260
00:29:36,361 --> 00:29:42,892
When we're going through any of the hindrances, we can feel anything but joyful and equanimous, for example.

261
00:29:44,335 --> 00:29:52,910
It needs the faith developed through long practice to trust that these factors are developing as we bear with the turmoil mindfully.

262
00:29:54,673 --> 00:30:00,343
Although we can't feel the factors in these situations, they're still contained within awareness.

263
00:30:01,707 --> 00:30:10,479
So long as we can maintain mindfulness, they're working away on our behalf and we'll settle back into our minds and hearts when conditions are right.

264
00:30:14,924 --> 00:30:22,855
As a quick recap on the factors of enlightenment, we have the image of wild geese in flight with their V-shaped formation.

265
00:30:24,386 --> 00:30:32,836
Mindfulness is in the lead, supported by three calming factors in the slipstream, concentration, equanimity and tranquillity.

266
00:30:34,196 --> 00:30:42,826
On the wide flank, pushing ahead, we have the three stimulating factors, energy, investigation of Dhamma and joy.

267
00:30:44,407 --> 00:30:48,893
These qualities of mind and heart are being developed whenever we meditate.

268
00:30:51,724 --> 00:30:54,809
Some of these also come to our aid in daily life.

269
00:30:55,991 --> 00:31:00,459
Here the Buddha gives another list, the five spiritual faculties.

270
00:31:01,902 --> 00:31:04,465
You'll not be surprised that mindfulness is here again.

271
00:31:05,728 --> 00:31:12,940
We slip into autopilot, not noticing anything about our surroundings or our inner life if we're not being mindful.

272
00:31:14,201 --> 00:31:23,594
We might be lost in daydreams and worries, not noticing how they're affecting our mood, posture, facial expression, tensions in the body, etc.

273
00:31:24,816 --> 00:31:36,611
So first and foremost, we need to wake up, notice that we've been lost in thought, bring ourselves back to the here and now, knowing experience as it's happening, mindful.

274
00:31:39,634 --> 00:31:43,500
When we're mindful, we'll also be on guard against wrongdoing.

275
00:31:44,813 --> 00:31:55,067
If we've got into a heated argument and are shouting and swearing it's very unlikely that we'll also be mindful deliberately and consciously choosing to shout and swear.

276
00:31:55,127 --> 00:32:01,217
The moment we wake up and notice what we're doing we'll start to calm down.

277
00:32:01,257 --> 00:32:05,963
The very discomfort of the body will deter us from continuing.

278
00:32:07,945 --> 00:32:13,233
So mindfulness protects us from going astray in daily life keeps us on the path

279
00:32:16,166 --> 00:32:18,630
That's not to say that anger is always unwholesome.

280
00:32:19,309 --> 00:32:21,772
There may be occasions when we need to shout and swear.

281
00:32:23,575 --> 00:32:29,980
But very often it happens for relatively trivial matters because someone's pushed a button.

282
00:32:31,663 --> 00:32:36,387
And in these situations we need to find other ways of dealing with the energies of anger.

283
00:32:38,990 --> 00:32:45,616
Although this is a long and often painful journey, mindfulness is our saving grace.

284
00:32:45,817 --> 00:32:50,301
rescuing us from old habits, showing us the potential for change.

285
00:32:54,186 --> 00:33:01,535
Just as in meditation, the balancing pair of energy and concentration support mindfulness in daily life.

286
00:33:03,497 --> 00:33:08,262
Energy here includes mental qualities like resolution and determination.

287
00:33:09,609 --> 00:33:15,760
as well as whatever physical energy we need to accomplish our goals, we won't give up easily.

288
00:33:18,023 --> 00:33:25,978
But of course we can get over energetic, doggedly following some fixed idea, not open to reason.

289
00:33:28,623 --> 00:33:30,806
Say we've asked some friends around for tea.

290
00:33:32,028 --> 00:33:34,031
We decide to bake a cake for them.

291
00:33:34,855 --> 00:33:36,196
But everything goes wrong.

292
00:33:37,218 --> 00:33:47,851
We don't have any eggs and the local shop is out of eggs and we have to drive 10 miles to get some and then we find we've run out of sugar and the mixer breaks down.

293
00:33:49,532 --> 00:33:53,917
Energy keeps us going, gets us through one problem after another.

294
00:33:55,220 --> 00:34:01,807
But we might still be beating eggs when our friends call and too frazzled to make them really welcome.

295
00:34:03,474 --> 00:34:06,857
So energy needs to be balanced by concentration.

296
00:34:09,440 --> 00:34:12,903
This reminds us that the aim is to have friends to tea.

297
00:34:13,965 --> 00:34:22,172
Baking a cake is secondary, grand if it works, but let's focus on the important point, to make our friends welcome.

298
00:34:24,414 --> 00:34:33,043
Concentration has a calming effect, keeps us directed, focuses our energies on what is beneficial.

299
00:34:36,128 --> 00:34:41,012
For daily life, we also need the support of faith and wisdom.

300
00:34:43,155 --> 00:34:48,320
Faith, Sharon Salzberg tells us, is not something you either have or have not.

301
00:34:49,101 --> 00:34:50,141
It's something you do.

302
00:34:50,181 --> 00:34:55,188
Faith in the Dhamma means to set your heart upon it.

303
00:34:56,989 --> 00:35:04,396
We start with what can be termed blind faith, accepting the teachings as true, even though we've no personal proof.

304
00:35:06,300 --> 00:35:20,648
As we practice and begin to see how we create suffering, how mindfulness reduces suffering, our initial blind faith turns to confidence in the teachings and gratitude for having received them.

305
00:35:22,601 --> 00:35:27,969
Faith, being a quality of the heart, warms up the teachings for us.

306
00:35:29,090 --> 00:35:39,766
We might develop a strong devotion towards the Buddha Dhamma Sangha, get more involved, be inspired to do our bit to support our local Sangha.

307
00:35:43,050 --> 00:35:47,277
There's always the danger in losing ourselves in devotion.

308
00:35:47,628 --> 00:35:55,476
idealising the Buddha or a teacher, rather than investigating whether the teachings are true in our own experience.

309
00:35:58,039 --> 00:36:00,681
Thus, faith needs the balance of wisdom.

310
00:36:03,666 --> 00:36:06,648
Wisdom starts with hearing or reading the Dhamma.

311
00:36:08,570 --> 00:36:14,056
It goes deeper when we reflect on this, think about how this applies to our life.

312
00:36:16,297 --> 00:36:25,568
The deepest wisdom comes from our meditation practice where we experience the teachings as moment to moment reality.

313
00:36:29,353 --> 00:36:42,507
The partnership of faith and wisdom is likened to a blind person who is energetic and strong pairing up with someone who is frail, crippled but with keen insight.

314
00:36:44,293 --> 00:36:50,240
The blind person symbolizes faith, while the frail person symbolizes wisdom.

315
00:36:52,023 --> 00:36:56,387
Wisdom sees where we want to go, but lacks strength on its own.

316
00:36:57,909 --> 00:37:01,893
It needs the power and energy of faith to make the journey.

317
00:37:07,380 --> 00:37:11,905
I think of faith and wisdom as a circle surrounding my life.

318
00:37:13,065 --> 00:37:16,710
They connect me up with the world, but also set limits.

319
00:37:18,172 --> 00:37:26,481
Within the circle I have energy and concentration, helping me do whatever tasks faith and wisdom have agreed on.

320
00:37:26,521 --> 00:37:35,731
At the very centre is mindfulness, seeing how all this activity relates to my present experience.

321
00:37:39,036 --> 00:37:49,990
I hope this talk has helped you understand the factors of enlightenment and how they relate to the spiritual faculties, which are the qualities we need and can develop in daily life.

322
00:37:51,213 --> 00:37:53,815
In both, mindfulness leads the way.

323
00:37:55,157 --> 00:38:04,690
Without mindfulness, our natural ability to know what is happening moment after moment, we backslide into old habits that lead to suffering.

324
00:38:06,947 --> 00:38:16,583
To keep mindfulness sharp, it is backed up by concentration, the ability to focus, to rest attention on some aspect of experience.

325
00:38:18,166 --> 00:38:23,534
And energy, the willingness to keep on going, no matter how hard it is.

326
00:38:26,739 --> 00:38:31,588
In daily life, this trio are further supported by faith and wisdom.

327
00:38:33,458 --> 00:38:54,117
In meditation, faith and wisdom keep developing with the aid of the twin supports of Dharma investigation, the drive to see the truth for ourselves, and equanimity, the balance of mind that allows us put up with what we dislike and to resist unnecessary enticements.

328
00:38:55,766 --> 00:39:13,829
and their heartfelt expressions as joy, a lively curiosity in moment-to-moment experience, and tranquillity, the quiet ease that comes from sensing that all is well, we're on the path, heading for home.

329
00:39:16,112 --> 00:39:20,677
May we soar like a flock of wild geese to liberation.

